tatus=live}}</ref> set by the Premiership Rugby Board, specifying the money a club can spend on the player salaries of its squad per season. In the 2017\u201318 season, the base cap was \u00a37 million, with an \"academy credit\" of up to \u00a3800,000 (\u00a3100,000 per player for up to eight players).\n\nA club may use the academy credit on a player that: (i) joined the club before his 18th birthday; (ii) is under age 24 at the start of the season; and (iii) earns a salary of more than \u00a330,000. Under the credit scheme, the first \u00a3100,000 of a qualifying player's salary is not counted against the cap.\n\n===Exclusions===\nSince the 2015\u201316 season, each club has been allowed to exclude two players from the cap calculations, an increase from one in prior seasons.\n\nThe first \"excluded player\" slot can be filled by any player on a team's current roster who meets any of the following criteria:\n* Played with his Premiership club for at least two full seasons before he was nominated as an excluded player.\n* Played with his Premiership club for the full season before being nominated as an excluded player, after having played outside the Premiership.\n* Played outside the Premiership in the season before he was nominated.\n\nThe second slot can only be filled by a player who had been outside the Premiership for at least one full season before signing his initial contract with his current Premiership club. For purposes of the exclusion rule, \"initial contract\" means the first contract signed for the 2015\u201316 season or later, meaning that a player who returned to a prior Premiership club after spending at least one full season outside the Premiership can qualify for the second slot.\n\n==Media coverage==\nIn the United Kingdom, the main rights are currently held by [[BT Sport]] under a new deal signed on 16 March 2015 replacing the former \u00a3152m deal signed on 12 September 2012. The new deal sees BT broadcast up to 80 live matches per season until the end of the 2020\u201321 season along with extended highlights of all matches and midweek programming.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/sep/12/bt-tv-rights-live-rugby|title=BT lands exclusive UK television rights to show live rugby union|website=theguardian.com|publisher=Guardian Media|date=12 September 2012|first=Josh|last=Halliday|accessdate=12 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025150141/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/sep/12/bt-tv-rights-live-rugby|archive-date=25 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=BT Sport extends Aviva Premiership rugby rights until 2021|url=http://sport.bt.com/rugby-union-hub/rugby-union/bt-sport-extends-aviva-premiership-rugby-rights-deal-until-2021-S11363968499263|website=BT Sport|publisher=British Telecom PLC|accessdate=16 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317161622/http://sport.bt.com/rugby-union-hub/rugby-union/bt-sport-extends-aviva-premiership-rugby-rights-deal-until-2021-S11363968499263|archive-date=17 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> UK rights are also held by [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] who will simulcast 5 matches live on a free-to-air basis, with a different commentary team as opposed to BT's commentary team, and also show a weekly highlights programme through the duration of BT's deal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Channel 5 to show live Premiership match for the first time on terrestrial TV|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/may/04/channel-5-premiership-rugby-live-terrestrial-tv|website=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Ltd.|accessdate=4 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504204045/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/may/04/channel-5-premiership-rugby-live-terrestrial-tv|archive-date=4 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In Australia the Premiership is available on [[beIN Sports (Australia)|beIN Sports]]. In the United States, the Premiership is available across [[NBC Sports]] since spring 2016. It will also be broadcast in [[China]] from 2017.\n\n[[Talksport]] and [[BBC Radio 5 Live]], along with various [[BBC Local Radio]] stations broadcast commentary and magazine programming.\n\n==See also==\n*[[English Rugby Union Leagues|Summary of the Current League positions for all English Leagues]]\n*[[Premiership Rugby A League]]\n*[[Anglo-Welsh Cup]]\n*[[Premiership Rugby Cup]]\n*[[List of English rugby union teams]]\n*[[European Professional Club Rugby]]\n*[[European Rugby Champions Cup]]\n*[[European Rugby Challenge Cup]]\n*[[European Shield]]\n*[[RFU Championship]]\n*[[Premiership Rugby Sevens Series]]\n*[[List of attendance figures at domestic professional sports leagues]]\n*[[List of English Rugby Union stadiums by capacity]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.premiershiprugby.com/}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100112040413/http://www.rugbyweek.com/GuinnessPremiership/ Guinness Premiership] Rugby Week\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/english/default.stm English rugby union news] BBC Sport\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090307235527/http://www.statbunker.com/rugby/ktg/index.php?PL=ktgalltime&Code=8217249&statType=tries All Time Premiership Records]\n\n{{English Premiership (rugby union)}}\n{{Original Courage League 1 clubs}}\n{{Rugby union in England}}\n{{Top-level rugby union club competitions}}\n{{Rugby union in Europe}}\n{{English and British National Champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:English Premiership (Rugby Union)}}\n[[Category:Premiership Rugby| ]]\n[[Category:Rugby union leagues in England|1]]\n[[Category:National rugby union premier leagues]]\n[[Category:Professional sports leagues in England]]\n[[Category:Sports leagues established in 1987]]\n[[Category:1987 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "109.180.211.26", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Premiership_Rugby"}
{"title_page": "1961\u201362 Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college basketball season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |mode=Basketball\n  |year=1961\u201362\n  |prev_year=1960\u201361\n  |next_year= 1962\u201363\n  |team=Cincinnati Bearcats\n  |image=1962_Cincinnati_Bearcats.jpg\n  |image_size=260px\n  |conference=Missouri Valley Conference \n  |division=\n  |short_conf=MVC\n  |CoachRank=2 \n  |APRank=2\n  |record=29\u20132\n  |conf_record=10\u20132\n  |head_coach=[[Ed Jucker]]\n  |hc_year=2nd\n  |asst_coach1=Tay Baker\n  |asst_coach2=\n  |asst_coach3=\n  |stadium=Armory Fieldhouse\n  |champion= NCAA champion<br>MVC champion\n  |bowl=[[1961 NCAA University Division Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]]\n  |bowl_result=Champions\n}}\nThe '''1961\u201362 Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball team''' represented [[University of Cincinnati]]. Cincinnati successfully defended its national championship with a 71\u201359 defeat of top-ranked [[1961\u201362 Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball team|Ohio State]] before 18,469 at [[Freedom Hall]] in [[Louisville, Kentucky]].<ref>Joseph M. Sheehan, Ohio State Bows, Bearcats Win, 71-59, for 2d N.C.A.A. Title -- Hogue Is Star, ''New York Times'', March 24, 1962</ref> The head coach was [[Ed Jucker]].\n\n==Season Summary==\nCincinnati played its way out from under the shadow of in-state rival [[Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball|Ohio State]] by winning two straight National Championships in 1961 and 1962, each time beating the Buckeyes in the title game. In 1962, the Bearcats were a deep, balanced team led by leading scorer and rebounded [[Paul Hogue]], a 6-foot-9 center. Five other player averaged between 8.2 and 14.3 points per game, and the Bearcats played stifling defense.\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CBB schedule start}}\n|-\n!colspan=12 style={{CollegePrimaryStyle|Cincinnati Bearcats}}|Regular Season\n{{CBB schedule entry\n| date         = December 2, 1961\n| w/l          = w