al period, the Bearcats were ahead by 18 points.\n\n==Awards and honors==\n\n{{Empty section|date=July 2010}}\n\n==NBA Draft==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=\"60%\"\n|- align=\"center\" style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Cincinnati Bearcats|color=white}}\"\n| '''Round''' || '''Pick''' || '''Player''' || '''NBA Club''' \n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"\"\n| 1 || 2 || Paul Hogue ||   New York Knicks\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"\"\n|}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.databasebasketball.com/draft/draftyear.htm?lg=N&yr=1962 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331185858/http://www.databasebasketball.com/draft/draftyear.htm?yr=1962&lg=N |archivedate=2008-03-31 }}</ref>\n\n*In the spring of 1962, [[Cleveland Pipers]] owner [[George Steinbrenner]] signed [[Jerry Lucas]] to a player-management contract worth forty thousand dollars.<ref>Steinbrenner: The Last Lion of Baseball, p.42, Bill Madden, Harper Collins Publishing, New York, 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-06-169031-0}}</ref> With the Lucas signing, Steinbrenner had a secret deal with NBA commissioner [[Maurice Podoloff]]. The Pipers would merge with the Kansas City Steers and join the NBA. A schedule was printed for the 1963\u201364 NBA season with the Pipers playing the New York Knicks in the first game.<ref>Steinbrenner: The Last Lion of Baseball, p.42, Bill Madden, Harper Collins Publishing, New York, 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-06-169031-0}}</ref> Steinbrenner and partner George McKean fell behind in payments to the NBA and the deal was cancelled.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1962 Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball navbox}}\n{{Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball navbox}}\n{{NCAA Men's Basketball Champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1961-62 Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball team}}\n[[Category:1961\u201362 Missouri Valley Conference men's basketball season|Cincinnati Bearcats]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball seasons]]\n[[Category:NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament championship seasons]]\n[[Category:NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament Final Four seasons]]\n[[Category:1962 NCAA University Division Basketball Tournament participants|Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:1961 in sports in Ohio|Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball]]\n[[Category:1962 in sports in Ohio|Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball]]\n[[Category:1962 in sports]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college basketball season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |mode=Basketball\n  |year=1961\u201362\n  |prev_year=1960\u201361\n  |next_year= 1962\u201363\n  |team=Cincinnati Bearcats\n  |image=1962_Cincinnati_Bearcats.jpg\n  |image_size=260px\n  |conference=Missouri Valley Conference \n  |division=\n  |short_conf=MVC\n  |CoachRank=2 \n  |APRank=2\n  |record=29\u20132\n  |conf_record=10\u20132\n  |head_coach=[[Ed Jucker]]\n  |hc_year=2nd\n  |asst_coach1=Tay Baker\n  |asst_coach2=\n  |asst_coach3=\n  |stadium=Armory Fieldhouse\n  |champion= NCAA champion<br>MVC champion\n  |bowl=[[1961 NCAA University Division Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]]\n  |bowl_result=Champions\n}}\nThe '''1961\u201362 Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball team''' represented [[University of Cincinnati]]. Cincinnati successfully defended its national championship with a 71\u201359 defeat of top-ranked [[1961\u201362 Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball team|Ohio State]] before 18,469 at [[Freedom Hall]] in [[Louisville, Kentucky]].<ref>Joseph M. Sheehan, Ohio State Bows, Bearcats Win, 71-59, for 2d N.C.A.A. Title -- Hogue Is Star, ''New York Times'', March 24, 1962</ref> The head coach was [[Ed Jucker]].\n\n==Season Summary==\nCincinnati played its way out from under the shadow of in-state rival [[Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball|Ohio State]] by winning two straight National Championships in 1961 and 1962, each time beating the Buckeyes in the title game. In 1962, the Bearcats were a deep, balanced team led by leading scorer and rebounded [[Paul Hogue]], a 6-foot-9 center. Five other player averaged between 8.2 and 14.3 points per game, and the Bearcats played stifling defense.\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CBB schedule start}}\n|-\n!colspan=12 style={{CollegePrimaryStyle|Cincinnati Bearcats}}|Regular Season\n{{CBB schedule entry\n| date         = December 5, 1961\n| w/l          = w\n| away         = \n| rank         = 2\n| nonconf      = yes\n| opponent     = {{cbb link|year=1961\u201362|ex=men|team=Miami Redskins|title=Miami (OH)}}\n| opprank      = \n| site_stadium = [[Armory Fieldhouse]]\n| site_cityst  = [[Cincinnati|Cincinnati, OH]]\n| score        = 63\u201330\n| record       = 1\u20130\n}}\n{{CBB schedule entry\n| date         = December 6, 1960\n| w/l          = w\n| away         = yes\n| rank         = 2\n| nonconf      = yes\n| opponent     = [[1961\u201362 Wisconsin Badgers men's basketball team|Wisconsin]]\n| opprank      = \n| site_stadium = [[Wisconsin Field House]]\n| site_cityst  = [[Madison, Wisconsin|Madison, WI]]\n| score        = 86\u201367\n| record       = 2\u20130\n}}\n{{CBB schedule entry\n| date         = December 11, 1961\n| w/l          = w\n| away         = yes\n| rank         = 2\n| nonconf      = \n| opponent     = {{cbb link|year=1961\u201362|ex=men|team=Drake Bulldogs|title=Drake}}\n| opprank      = \n| site_stadium = [[Community Choice Credit Union Convention Center|Veterans Memorial Auditorium]]\n| site_cityst  = [[Des Moines|Des Moines, IA]]\n| score        = 60\u201359\n| record       = 3\u20130\n| conference   = 1\u20130\n}}\n{{CBB schedule entry\n| date         = December 16, 1961\n| w/l          = w\n| away         = \n| rank         = 2\n| nonconf      = yes\n| opponent     = {{cbb link|year=1961\u201362|ex=men|team=Marshall Thundering Herd|title=Marshall}}\n| opprank      = \n| site_stadium = Armory Fieldhouse\n| site_cityst  = Cincinnati, OH\n| score        = 77\u201349\n| record       = 4\u20130\n}}\n{{CBB schedule entry\n| date         = December 18, 1961\n| w/l          = l\n| away     